# Who Wired This - Architecture

## Core Runtime Pattern
- Managers are scene singletons (`GameManager`, `ScoreManager`, `TimerManager`, `InventoryManager`, `HUDController`, `MessagePanel`)
- Singleton setup pattern:
  - `if (Instance != null && Instance != this) { Destroy(gameObject); return; }`
  - `Instance = this;`
- No cross-scene persistence pattern is currently used (`DontDestroyOnLoad` is not part of this architecture)

## Interaction Model
- Nearby interactions use interface-driven discovery:
  - `IInteractable.GetPromptText()`
  - `IInteractable.Interact(GameObject interactor)`
- Player interaction scan currently uses `Physics.OverlapSphere` + nearest candidate selection
- UI prompt updates only when candidate changes (`HUDController.SetInteractPrompt(...)`)

## Inventory/Puzzle Contract
- Inventory capacity is fixed (`MaxSlots = 3`)
- Puzzle item matching is ID-based via `ItemData.itemId`
- `TestButton` validates socketed `ItemData.itemId` against expected IDs
- Preserve this contract when adding new puzzle items or sockets

## Event Wiring Expectations
- Managers expose events (for example score/timer/zone changes)
- UI subscribers should detach listeners during teardown
- Avoid hidden side effects in event handlers; keep handlers focused on UI/state refresh

## Safe Extension Guidelines
- Prefer extending existing systems (`IInteractable`, manager events, UI refresh APIs) over creating parallel systems
- Keep user-facing strings centralized in the owning component (for example help/about text in `HUDController`)
- Keep scene reference wiring inspector-driven for UI and interactables
- Prefer using existing scene objects instead of creating runtime objects in code
- Use prefabs for repeatable objects with gameplay meaning (interactables, machines, pickups, reusable UI blocks)
- Connect scene objects to scripts via serialized inspector properties (`[SerializeField]`) rather than lookup/creation code
